ips to map data into trees</h4><p class=3D"styles__Paragraph-fvdpr4-5 hNKcs=
f"><strong class=3D"styles__Strong-fvdpr4-15 eHeecn">Initial introduction: =
1960s</strong></p><p class=3D"styles__Paragraph-fvdpr4-5 hNKcsf">Hierarchic=
al databases were the next evolution in database management development.  T=
hey encode a relationship between items where every record has a single par=
ent.  This builds a tree-like structure that can be used to categorize reco=
rds according to their parent record.</p><p class=3D"styles__Paragraph-fvdp=
r4-5 hNKcsf"><span class=3D"Image__Wrapper-sc-152tu6s-0 iUrdCz"><img class=
=3D"Image-sc-152tu6s-1 cmQiWS" src=3D"https://www.prisma.io/blog/posts/data=
base-type-comparison/hierarchical.png" alt=3D"Diagram of a hierarchical dat=
abase"><span class=3D"Image__Title-sc-152tu6s-2 uHBje">Diagram of a hierarc=
hical database</span></span></p><p class=3D"styles__Paragraph-fvdpr4-5 hNKc=
sf">This simple relationship mapping provides users with the ability to est=
ablish relationships between items in a tree structure.  This is very usefu=
l for certain types of data, but does not allow for complex relationship ma=
nagement.  Furthermore, the meaning of the parent-child relationship is imp=
licit.  One parent-child connection could be between a customer and their o=
rders, while another might represent an employee and the equipment they hav=
e been allocated.  The structure of the data itself does not distinguish be=
tween these relationships.</p><p class=3D"styles__Paragraph-fvdpr4-5 hNKcsf=
">Hierarchical databases are the beginning of a movement towards thinking a=
bout data management in more complex terms.  The trajectory of database man=
agement systems that were developed afterwards continues this trend.</p><p =
class=3D"styles__Paragraph-fvdpr4-5 hNKcsf">Hierarchical databases are not =
used much today due to their limited ability to organize most data and beca=
use of the overhead of accessing data by traversing the hierarchy.  However=
, a few incredibly important systems could be considered hierarchical datab=
ases.  A filesystem, for instance, can be thought of as a specialized hiera=
rchical database, as the system of files and directories fit neatly into th=
e single-parent / multiple-child paradigm.  Likewise, DNS and LDAP systems =
both act as databases for hierarchical datasets.</p><p class=3D"styles__Par=
agraph-fvdpr4-5 hNKcsf">Examples:</p><ul class=3D"styles__Ul-fvdpr4-2 fpttB=
k"><li class=3D"styles__Li-fvdpr4-4 lcXSUH"><a target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener noreferrer" class=3D"styles__A-fvdpr4-7 hLlHFt" href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/File_system">Filesystems</a></li><li class=3D"styles__Li-f=
